TWO-TIME Emmy Award nominee Loyiso Gola has scored his own Netflix gig. He’ll become the first ever African comedian to enjoy an hour of stand-up comedy on the streaming platform. Netflix announced that Loyiso’s show, Unlearning, will debut next month. “It’s no secret that globally we’ve been going through a time and could all do with a laugh or two right now,” said Netflix. “Loyiso is back on Netflix and ready with his sharp wit and critically acclaimed comedy hour, Unlearning, debuting globally on 23 March 2021.” Loyiso will make history as the only African comedian to enjoy an hour of stand-up comedy on the platform. ALSO READ | ACTRESS: ONLY FANS SENSATION “Loyiso, who’ll explore his own experience of maturity and masculinity during apartheid in South Africa, is the first African to have a solo full hour of stand-up comedy on Netflix,” said Netflix. “And that’s not all – this is the first African original for 2021.” Fact file: * Included in his many impressive achievements, Loyiso is a two-time Emmy nominee for his satirical news TV series, Late Nite News with Loyiso Gola, which launched in 2010 and had 12 seasons. * He’s the African correspondent for The Weekly with Charlie Pickering on ABC in Australia. * Some of his noteworthy performances include his show Tall Tales, which ran at the Soho Theatre in 2015; Dude, Where’s My Lion?, which ran in Edinburgh; Loyiso Gola Live in New York, his debut US stand-up special recorded in Brooklyn in 2016; and the Netflix special Comedians of the World, released in 2019. * In 2017, Loyiso debuted his now critically acclaimed one-hour special, Unlearning in Edinburgh, then later at London’s Soho Theatre and the Melbourne Comedy Special. He’s now bringing Unlearning to his hometown, Cape Town, filmed at the Zeitz Mocca.